  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a phenomenon where individuals from underrepresented groups experience anxiety about confirming negative stereotypes about their group's abilities, which can impair their performance. As a retired woman who grew up in Milan with a vocational diploma and a father who was a PhD holder, I've witnessed how stereotypes can linger even in seemingly progressive spaces. My own experiences with depression and the quiet pressure of being one of the few women in my field during my working years taught me that when people internalize the idea that they're 'not good at math,' their confidence drops, and they disengage. We should address stereotype threat because it directly impacts learning and retention—especially for girls and minorities in STEM. But the solution isn't just awareness; it's creating environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes. I've seen this in my garden: when you plant seeds without fear of failure, they grow. Similarly, in classrooms, if students are told they're 'smart' instead of 'good at math,' they're more likely to persist. My advice is simple: educators should focus on growth mindset, celebrate diverse contributions, and avoid language that reinforces stereotypes. It's not about fixing the problem but nurturing a space where everyone feels they belong. This is especially critical in Italy, where STEM education has historically been male-dominated. I hope my grandchildren will grow up in a world where their potential isn't limited by what others think they can do.",
